UK 2012 Accidents Dataset - SVM and Logistic Regression¶

MSDS 7331 Data Mining - Section 403 - Mini-Lab¶

Group 3: Bhuvana Adur Kannan, Selwyn Samuel, Anjli Solsi¶

Summary¶

The primary focus of this mini lab is to use Support Vector Machines (SVM) and Logistic Regression to analyze and predict the severity of traffic accidents in the UK (major=1, minor=0). This involves performing exploratory data analysis on the dataset including dealing with missing data using various data imputation techniques and optimizing the number of features using dimensionality reduction and other techniques.

Business Understanding¶

The UK government has gathered traffic accident data from the years 2000 to 2016, capturing data for over 1.6 million accidents. The data is collected from police reports and does not include fender bender type incidents. In order to reduce the complexity and resource requirements, we will be working on the accidents occured during 2012.

This dataset is originally from the UK government website but is hosted by BigML Inc. It can be downloaded fro the link: https://bigml.com/user/czuriaga/gallery/dataset/525dcd15035d076e7f00e3ac.

Data Quality¶

Duplicate Data¶

Some of the records in the dataset appear to be duplicate, but that was not the case once they were observed closely. When two or more vehicles are involved in an accident, there is an instance for each vehicle with the location and other features being the same; however, the driver and vehicle information is different.

Missing Values¶

  • The 1st Road Number and the 2nd Road Number attributes have a considerable number of missing values. Based on our understanding of the data we will drop these features as the road numbers may not have a direct impact on the accident severity.
  • LSOA (Lower layer Super Output) of Accident Location has a few thousand missing values. Lower Layer Super Output Areas are a geographic hierarchy designed to improve the reporting of small area statistics in England and Wales. Since we have the accident latitude and longitude attributes, we can drop the entire feature.
  • Engine Capacity, Age of Vehicle and Propulsion Code have a few thousand missing values. Instead of imputing the mean or median values for these continuous attributes, we will delete the instances with missing values as we have enough instances for our analysis and prediction.

Removing attributes¶

Based on our undestanding and manual analysis of the data, the following attributes will be removed as they are related to accident severity.

  • Date.year: We have already limited our dataset to 2012 data.
  • Date: We have separate attributes for month, day, hour, minute and second.
  • Location Easting OSGR and Location Northing OSGR are geographic Cartesian coordinates for a point. They can be removed as we have latitudes and longitudes.
  • We will remove Police Force, Local Authority (District) and Local Authority (Highway) as they are informational categorical attributes that may not have an impact on the accident severity.
  • 1st Road Class and 2nd Road class have large number of 'Unclassified' data and we will drop those attributes as well.
  • Pedestrian Crossing-Human Control has most of its value as 'None within 50 metres' which may not be very useful in prediction.
  • Pedestrian Crossing-Physical Facilities has most of its value as 'No physical crossing facilities within 50 metres' which may not be very useful in prediction.
  • Special Conditions at Site has most of its value as 'None' which may not be very useful in prediction.
  • Carriageway Hazards at Site has most of its value as 'None' which may not be very useful in prediction.
  • Did Police Officer Attend happens after the accident and will not have an impact on the accident severity.
  • Towing and Articulation has most of the values as 'No tow/articulation', 'Other tow' or 'Data missing or out of range' which may not be very useful in prediction.
  • Vehicle Location-Restricted Lane has most of its value as 'On main c'way - not in restricted lane' which may not be very useful in prediction.

New attributes¶

Since the goal is to perform logistic regression analysis, we would need the response attribute to take 0 or 1 values. Currently Accident Severity has 'Fatal', 'Serious' and 'Slight' values. We will define a new attribute Major Accident with 1 or 0 values. We will classify the instances with Accident Severity as 'Fatal' and 'Serious' as Major Accident with value 1 and the Slight instances as 0.

We will need to perform one hot encoding for all the categorical variables.

In [2]:
# Remove unwanted attributes
df.drop(['1st Road Number', '2nd Road Number', 'Date', 'Date.year', 'Location Easting OSGR', 'Location Northing OSGR', 
         'Local Authority (District)', 'Local Authority (Highway)', '1st Road Class', '2nd Road Class', 
         'Pedestrian Crossing-Human Control', 'Pedestrian Crossing-Physical Facilities', 'Special Conditions at Site', 
         'Carriageway Hazards', 'Did Police Officer Attend', 'LSOA of Accident Location', 'Towing and Articulation', 
         'Vehicle Location-Restricted Lane', 'Police Force'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# Drop all the instances with NaN values
df.dropna(inplace=True)

# Create a new attribute 'Major Accident' with 1 or 0 values based on accident severity
def mapAccidentSeverity(severity):
    if(severity == 'Fatal'):
        return 1;
    if(severity == 'Serious'):
        return 1;
    if(severity == 'Slight'):
        return 0;

df['Major Accident'] = df['Accident Severity'].map(mapAccidentSeverity)
df.drop(['Accident Severity'], axis=1, inplace=True)

print(df.shape)
print(df.info())
print('Majot Accidents count split: ', df['Major Accident'].value_counts())

One hot encoding of Categorical attributes¶

In [3]:
# List all the categorical attributes identified for one hot encoding
categorical_attributes = ['Road Type', 'Junction Detail', 'Junction Control', 'Light Conditions', 'Weather Conditions', 
                          'Road Surface Conditions', 'Urban or Rural Area', 'Vehicle Type', 'Vehicle Manoeuvre', 
                          'Junction Location', 'Skidding and Overturning', 'Hit Object in Carriageway', 
                          'Vehicle Leaving Carriageway', 'Hit Object off Carriageway', '1st Point of Impact', 
                          'Was Vehicle Left Hand Drive?', 'Journey Purpose of Driver', 'Sex of Driver', 'Age Band of Driver', 
                          'Propulsion Code', 'Driver IMD Decile', 'Driver Home Area Type']

# Change the data type for the categorical attributes
for feature in list(df.columns):
    if feature in categorical_attributes:
        df[feature] = df[feature].astype('category')

# one hot encoding
X = pd.get_dummies(df, sparse=True)

y = X['Major Accident']
X.drop(['Major Accident'], axis=1, inplace=True)

print(X.shape)

In [10]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
import pylab as pl

def drawConfusionMatrix(y_test, y_pred, labels, model):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred, labels)
    print(cm)
    fig = plt.figure()
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    cax = ax.matshow(cm)
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix for '+model)
    fig.colorbar(cax)
    ax.set_xticklabels([''] + labels)
    ax.set_yticklabels([''] + labels)
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('True')
    plt.show()
    return

Support Vector Machine Model¶

This model relies upon kernel functions that work to classify observations into one or more classes. In this case, this method is used to predict accident severity based upon the model created using training data. The linear and radial basis function (RBF) kernel are explored below.

The table below has been added as the table above from the python code is not displayed unless executed.

The above table lists the different models ran on the dataset with the accuracy of the model, time taken to train, time taken to predict & the number of misclassified samples. The Logistic Regression model offers the best accuracy among all the other models, which is 86.17%, taking 31.1 seconds to train 80% of the train data, and only 0.02 seconds to predict 20% of the test data.

The time taken to train increases from 3.43 seconds for the Perceptron Model to 31.67 seconds for the Logistic Regression Model. This is a significant increase, which is 10 times more for Logistic Regression, but this model also improves accuracy from 79% to 86%.

The misclassified samples remains as 7977 for almost all the models.

The model with least accuracy is the SVM with linear kernel, having only 45.06% accuracy. The reason behind this is probably due to the fact that the data is not linearly seperable.

Interpret Feature Importance¶

This section focuses on assigning weights to each feature to understand how important each attribute is for predicting the severity of an accident. The first step is to determine the individual weights of each variable. Due to the range of differences in attributes, the data has to be normalized to show a scaled weight between 0 and 1, which is accomplished by using the StandardScaler function of scikit-learn. We only fit the training data to ensure no data snooping occurs, and use a small value of C so that the weights are kept to a reasonable amount to guard against overfitting the model to the data.

Visualizations¶

As per the graph below, the importance of each variable, whether positive or negative, are compared against each other. From analysis, the following conclusions may be drawn in order to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset:

  • Driver IMD Decile: This is a value that shows the relative deprivation level of the area the casualty or driver involved in the crash lives. Based on the graphs, this attribute does not contribute to the outcome and could be removed in the future.
  • Propulsion Code: This attribute also does not contribute to the outcome and could be removed in the future.

Based on the graph of the coefficients for the logistic regression model, the 3 most significantly weighted predictors are junction location, junction detail, and junction control. These predictors all have coefficient values close to or above 0.5 (or below -0.5 in the case of the first two), meaning that they contribute the most heavily to the model. We are confident that these variables have the highest contribution to accident severity, since the variables were scaled to match the other categorical predictor scales prior to the weighting of these coefficients.

Some other attributes that have a significant contribution to the model, based on the logistic regression coefficient plot below are number of casualties and vehicle type.

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Code from https://medium.com/@aneesha/visualising-top-features-in-linear-svm-with-scikit-learn-and-matplotlib-3454ab18a14d
def plot_coefficients(classifier, feature_names, top_features=10):
    coef = classifier.coef_.ravel()
    top_positive_coefficients = np.argsort(coef)[-top_features:]
    top_negative_coefficients = np.argsort(coef)[:top_features]
    top_coefficients = np.hstack([top_negative_coefficients, top_positive_coefficients])
    # create plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    colors = ['red' if c < 0 else 'blue' for c in coef[top_coefficients]]
    plt.bar(np.arange(2 * top_features), coef[top_coefficients], color=colors)
    feature_names = np.array(feature_names)
    plt.xticks(np.arange(1, 1 + 2 * top_features), feature_names[top_coefficients], rotation=60, ha='right')
    plt.show()

Interpret Support Vectors¶

Examining our coefficients shows that some variables are stronger than others for influencing accident severity, with quite a difference from the logistic regression analysis. Having a strong positive coefficient are attributes such as: driver home area type, age band of driver, journey purpose, vehicle maneuver, vehicle type, and light conditions. It is worth noting that these were not found to be contributing factors in the logistic regression model. Having a strong negative coefficient are attributes such as: many of the previous ones, hit object in carriageway, junction location, junction detail, and number of casualties. Some of these were found to be contributing factors in the logistic regression model. Overall, the linear svm seems to have many attributes with higher weights than the logistic regression model.

Additional rbf analysis was performed, and based on the accuracies noted in the models, does not appear to be more effective than the linear svm.

Based on our analysis, a linear svm does not appear to be an appropriate solution for this dataset and is too idealistic. This means that we cannot reasonably draw a dividing line with a linear svm given the overlap in our data in multidimensional space.
